<chapter xml:id="chapter-permutations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Permutations</title>

<section xml:id="section-permutations-factorials">
<title>Factorials</title>

<p>
In counting, factorials come up a lot.
<dl>
	<li>
		<title><m>n!</m></title>
		<idx>factorial</idx>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>n!</m></usage>
			<description>factorial <m>n! = n (n - 1) (n - 2) \dotsm 2 \cdot 1</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		notation for the computation formula <me> n (n - 1) (n - 2) \dotsm 2 \cdot 1 </me>,
		for natural number <m>n</m>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl>
</p>

<example>
	<title>Two factorial calculations</title>
	<p><md><mrow>
		3! \amp = 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 = 6, \amp
		7! = 7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 = 5,040.
	</mrow></md></p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Factorial factors</title>
	<p>
	A factorial contains every smaller factorial as a factor.
	For example,
	<me>
		\frac{7!}{3!}
		= \frac{
			7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5 \cdot 4 \cdot \cancel{(3!)}
		}{
			\cancel{3!}
		}
		= 7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5 \cdot 4 = 840
	</me>.
	</p>
</example>

<convention xml:id="convention-permutations-0-factorial"><p>
	To avoid division by zero in certain formulas, define <m>0! = 1</m>.
	This choice is also made to be consistent with the methods for counting permutations we will explore in this chapter.
</p></convention>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-permutations-defn">
<title>Definition</title>

<p> We often want to count how many ways we can <q>mix up</q> the objects in a collection. </p>

<p><dl><li>
	<title>permutation</title>
	<idx>permutation</idx>
	<idx><h>function</h><h>permutation</h></idx>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>permutation</h></idx>
	<p> a bijection from a finite set to itself </p>
</li></dl></p>

<remark><p>
	Once you have written the elements of a finite set in some order,
	think of a permutation as a way of <em>re-ordering</em> them.
</p></remark>

<example>
	<title>Permutations of three objects</title>
	<p>
	<xref ref="figure-permutations-all-on-three-objects" />
	contains tables of values for all six possible permutations of the set <m>A = \{a,b,c\}</m>.
	We have grouped them according to:
	all elements fixed;
	one element fixed and two mixed;
	all elements mixed.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-permutations-all-on-three-objects">
		<caption>All possible permutations on three objects.</caption>
		<sidebyside>
			<tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" halign="center">
				<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col />
				<row bottom="minor">
					<cell><m>x</m></cell>
					<cell><m>a</m></cell>
					<cell><m>b</m></cell>
					<cell><m>c</m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><m>\id_A(x)</m></cell>
					<cell><m>a</m></cell>
					<cell><m>b</m></cell>
					<cell><m>c</m></cell>
				</row>
			</tabular>
			<tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" halign="center">
				<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col />
				<row bottom="minor">
					<cell><m>x</m></cell>
					<cell><m>a</m></cell>
					<cell><m>b</m></cell>
					<cell><m>c</m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><m>f_a(x)</m></cell>
					<cell><m>a</m></cell>
					<cell><m>c</m></cell>
					<cell><m>b</m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><m>f_b(x)</m></cell>
					<cell><m>c</m></cell>
					<cell><m>b</m></cell>
					<cell><m>a</m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><m>f_c(x)</m></cell>
					<cell><m>b</m></cell>
					<cell><m>a</m></cell>
					<cell><m>c</m></cell>
				</row>
			</tabular>
			<tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" halign="center">
				<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col />
				<row bottom="minor">
					<cell><m>x</m></cell>
					<cell><m>a</m></cell>
					<cell><m>b</m></cell>
					<cell><m>c</m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><m>s_r(x)</m></cell>
					<cell><m>c</m></cell>
					<cell><m>a</m></cell>
					<cell><m>b</m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><m>s_l(x)</m></cell>
					<cell><m>b</m></cell>
					<cell><m>c</m></cell>
					<cell><m>a</m></cell>
				</row>
			</tabular>
		</sidebyside>
	</figure>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-permutations-counting">
<title>Counting permutations</title>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-permutations-counting">
	<statement><p> For <m>\card{A} = n</m>, there are <m>n!</m> permutations on <m>A</m>. </p></statement>
	<proof><title>Informal proof</title><p>
		We want to count the number of ways of constructing an ordered list of the <m>n</m> elements of <m>A</m>.
		There are <m>n</m> ways to choose the first element in the list,
		<m>n-1</m> ways to choose the second,
		<m>n-2</m> ways to choose the third,
		and so on,
		ending at a single way to choose the <m>\nth</m>.
		By the <xref ref="theorem-counting-mult-rule" text="title" />, there are
		<me> n \cdot (n - 1) \cdot (n - 2) \cdot \dotsb \cdot 1 = n! </me>
		ways to construct such a list.
	</p></proof>
	<proof><title>Formal proof</title>
		<p> By induction. </p>
		<case><title>Base case <m>n=1</m></title><p>
			If <m>\card{A} = 1</m>, then <m>A</m> consists of a single element, say <m>A = \{a\}</m>.
			There is only one possible permutation of <m>A</m>, and that is the identity function <m>\funcdef{\id_A}{A}{A}</m> defined by <m>\id_A(a) = a</m>.
			Thus, we have verified that there is <m>1! = 1</m> permutation of <m>A</m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Induction step</title>
			<p>
			Let <m>k \ge 1</m> be a fixed integer.
			Our induction hypothesis is to assume that if <m>B</m> is any set with <m>\card{B} = k</m> elements,
			then there are <m>k!</m> permutations on <m>B</m>.
			We want to use this hypothesis to prove that if <m>A</m> is a set with <m>\card{A} = k+1</m> elements,
			then there are <m>(k+1)!</m> permutations on <m>A</m>.
			</p><p>
			Write <m>A = \{ a_0, a_1, \dotsc, a_k \}</m> and <m>B = \{ a_1, a_2, \dotsc, a_k \}</m>.
			Then <m>B</m> is a subset of <m>A</m> that contains <m>k</m> elements,
			and so by our induction hypothesis there are <m>k!</m> permutations on <m>B</m>.
			For every such permutation of <m>B</m>, we can construct <m>k+1</m> permutations of <m>A</m> by <q>inserting</q> <m>a_0</m> at different positions in the output list.
			For example, consider how the identity permutation on <m>B</m> can be turned into <m>k+1</m> different permutations on <m>A</m> <mdash />
			see <xref ref="figure-permutations-induction-insert" />.
			</p>
			<figure xml:id="figure-permutations-induction-insert">
				<caption>Inserting an extra element at various positions of a permutation to create new, longer permutations.</caption>
				<sidebyside><stack>
					<tabular top="medium" halign="center">
						<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col />
						<row bottom="minor">
							<cell><m>x</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_2</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_3</m></cell>
							<cell><ellipsis /></cell>
							<cell><m>a_{k-1}</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_k</m></cell>
						</row>
						<row bottom="medium">
							<cell><m>\id_B(x)</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_2</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_3</m></cell>
							<cell><ellipsis /></cell>
							<cell><m>a_{k-1}</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_k</m></cell>
						</row>
					</tabular>
					<p><me>\downarrow</me></p>
					<tabular top="medium" bottom="minor" halign="center">
						<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col />
						<!-- <row bottom="minor"> -->
						<row>
							<cell><m>x</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_0</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_2</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_3</m></cell>
							<cell><ellipsis /></cell>
							<cell><m>a_{k-1}</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_k</m></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>\id_B^{(0)}(x) = \id_A(x)</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_0</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_2</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_3</m></cell>
							<cell><ellipsis /></cell>
							<cell><m>a_{k-1}</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_k</m></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>\id_B^{(1)}(x)</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_0</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_2</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_3</m></cell>
							<cell><ellipsis /></cell>
							<cell><m>a_{k-1}</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_k</m></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>\id_B^{(2)}(x)</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_2</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_0</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_3</m></cell>
							<cell><ellipsis /></cell>
							<cell><m>a_{k-1}</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_k</m></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>\id_B^{(3)}(x)</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_2</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_3</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_0</m></cell>
							<cell><ellipsis /></cell>
							<cell><m>a_{k-1}</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_k</m></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
							<cell />
							<cell />
							<cell />
							<cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
							<cell />
							<cell />
							<cell />
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>\id_B^{(k-1)}(x)</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_2</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_3</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_4</m></cell>
							<cell><ellipsis /></cell>
							<cell><m>a_0</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_k</m></cell>
						</row>
						<row bottom="medium">
							<cell><m>\id_B^{(k)}(x)</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_2</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_3</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_4</m></cell>
							<cell><ellipsis /></cell>
							<cell><m>a_k</m></cell>
							<cell><m>a_0</m></cell>
						</row>
					</tabular>
				</stack></sidebyside>
			</figure>
			<p>
			<em>Each</em> of the <m>k!</m> permutations of <m>B</m> can be used to construct <m>k+1</m> permutations of <m>A</m>, in the same fashion as we have above for the identity permutation of <m>B</m>.
			So we have in total <m>(k+1) \cdot k! = (k+1)!</m> permutations of <m>A</m>, as required.
			</p>
		</case>
	</proof>
</theorem>

<remark><p>
	When applying the method of mathematical induction in the formal proof,
	we began our base case at <m>n = 1</m>.
	But the formula <m>n!</m> is still valid for the number of permutations of the empty set.
	In this case, <m>n = 0</m> and so <m>n! = 0! = 1</m> by <xref ref="convention-permutations-0-factorial" />.
	And there is indeed exactly one permutation of the empty set <mdash />
	the <xref ref="definition-cardinality-empty-function" text="title" />.
	(See <xref ref="proposition-cardinality-empty-functions-bij" text="local">Statement</xref>
	of <xref ref="proposition-cardinality-empty-functions" />.)
</p></remark>

<p>
Each of the provided proofs for <xref ref="theorem-permutations-counting" /> above contains an idea that is of practical use in counting collections.
<ul>
	<li>
		In the informal proof,
		we used the <xref ref="theorem-counting-mult-rule" text="title" />
		to count the number of ways to construct an ordered list,
		where the tasks in the construction are choosing the elements in the list one at a time.
		(We used this similar thinking often in <xref ref="chapter-counting" />,
		though we didn't explicitly connect the <xref ref="theorem-counting-mult-rule" text="title" /> to ordered lists.)
	</li>
	<li>
		In the formal proof, we used the idea of <q>inserting</q> an object into an existing ordered list to create a new ordered list.
	</li>
</ul>
</p>

<problem>  <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Distributing items</title>
	<statement><p>
		For a class of twenty students,
		in how many different orders can a professor hand back marked tests:
		<ol>
			<li> In total? </li>
			<li> If Karishma's test must be handed back first? </li>
			<li> If Elizabeth's and Ruijing's tests cannot immediately follow one another? </li>
		</ol>
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p><ol>
		<li>
			A test distribution order is the same thing as a permutation of the students in the class,
			so there are <m>20!</m> different handback orders
			(approximately <m>2.4</m> quintillion).
		</li>
		<li>
			This is just the number of ways of ordering the remaining nineteen students' papers,
			which is <m>19!</m>
			(approximately <m>122</m> quadrillion).
		</li>
		<li>
			It is easier to count the ways that they <em>do</em> follow each other.
			One way to do this is as follows.
			Remove Elizabeth's test from the pile.
			There are now <m>19!</m> ways to order the remaining nineteen papers.
			There are two ways to insert Elizabeth's test back into any such ordering <mdash />
			either immediately before or after Ruijing's paper.
			So there are <m>2 \cdot 19!</m> orderings we <em>do not</em> want.
			Therefore, applying the <xref ref="theorem-counting-subtr-rule" text="title" />
			yields answer
			<me>
				20! - 2 \cdot 19!
				= 20 \cdot 19! - 2 \cdot 19!
				= 18 \cdot 19!
			</me>.
		</li>
	</ol></p></solution>
</problem>

<problem xml:id="wexample-permutations-counting-words">  <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Words using the entire alphabet</title>
	<statement><p>
		For an alphabet <m>\Sigma</m> with <m>\card{\Sigma} = n</m>,
		how many words in <m>\words{\Sigma}</m> contain each element of the alphabet exactly once?
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p> Here we just want to order all the elements of <m>\Sigma</m> into a word, so the answer is <m>n!</m>. </p>
		<aside><title>Compare</title><p> See <xref ref="wexample-counting-words-no-repeats" />. </p></aside>
	</solution>
</problem>

<remark><p>
	<xref ref="wexample-permutations-counting-words" /> justifies the convention <m>0! = 1</m>,
	since if <m>\card{\Sigma} = 0</m>, then <m>\words{\Sigma}</m> contains exactly one word:
	the empty word <m>\emptyword</m>.
	And in this case it is vacuously true that <m>\emptyword</m> contains each element of <m>\Sigma</m> exactly once.
</p></remark>

<problem>  <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Counting total orders</title>
	<statement><p> If <m>\card{A} = n</m>, how many different total orders on <m>A</m> exist? </p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Specifying a total order on <m>A</m> really just means ordering the elements of <m>A</m>:
		<me> a_1 \le a_2 \le a_3 \le \dotsb \le a_n. </me>
		So there are <m>n!</m> possible total orders.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<problem xml:id="wexample-permutations-bottle-colour-patterns">  <!-- worked example -->
<!-- \label{WEXAMPLE::bottle.colour.patterns.1} -->
	<title>Counting colour patterns</title>
	<statement><p>
		How many different colour patterns can we obtain by placing three red bottles and five blue bottles on a shelf?
		(Assume the bottles are indistinguishable except by colour.)
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Let's use the <xref ref="theorem-counting-div-rule" text="title" />,
		where first we will count a more structured collection.
		If the bottles of the same colour <em>were</em> distinguishable from each other,
		we would have <m>8!</m> ways of lining them up on the shelf.
		Assuming indistinguishability, we now consider two orderings with the same colour pattern but mixed up red and/or blue bottles to be <em>equivalent</em>.
		For example, the two orderings
		<md>
			<mrow> \mathrm{R}_1 \; \mathrm{B}_1 \; \mathrm{B}_2 \; \mathrm{R}_2 \; \mathrm{R}_3 \; \mathrm{B}_3 \; \mathrm{B}_4 \; \mathrm{B}_5, </mrow>
			<mrow> \mathrm{R}_2 \; \mathrm{B}_5 \; \mathrm{B}_3 \; \mathrm{R}_1 \; \mathrm{R}_3 \; \mathrm{B}_1 \; \mathrm{B}_4 \; \mathrm{B}_2, </mrow>
		</md>
		of distinguishable bottles create the same colour pattern, and so are equivalent.
		Once red and blue bottle positions are determined, we can permute the reds (<m>3!</m> ways) and blues (<m>5!</m> ways) independently,
		so each equivalence class inside the collection of orderings of <em>distinguishable</em> bottles contains <m>3! \cdot 5!</m> equivalent orderings.
		Applying the <xref ref="theorem-counting-div-rule" text="title" />,
		we arrive at
		<me> \frac{8!}{3! \cdot 5!} = \frac{8\cdot 7 \cdot 6}{3 \cdot 2} = 56 </me>
		possible colour patterns.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<problem>  <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Circular orderings</title>
	<statement><p>
		How many different seating arrangements of ten people around a round table are possible,
		if no one is considered to be at the <q>head</q> or <q>foot</q> of the table?
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Let's use the <xref ref="theorem-counting-div-rule" text="title" />,
		where first we will count a more structured collection.
		There are <m>10!</m> ways to line the <m>10</m> people up.
		Wrapping the end of the line around to meet the beginning forms a circular seating arrangement.
		But <q>rotating</q> around the line (<m>10</m> possible rotations) yields an equivalent circular seating arrangement.
		So the answer is <me> \frac{10!}{10} = 9! </me>.
	</p></solution>
	<solution><p>
		Force one particular person to <em>always</em> be the <q>start</q> of the seating arrangement,
		no matter what physical seat they are sitting in,
		and ignoring the fact that a circular arrangement really has no <q>start.</q>
		Then there are <m>9!</m> ways to arrange the remaining <m>9</m> people around the table starting from the seat to the left of the <q>start</q> person.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-permutations-subsets">
<title>Permutations of subsets</title>

<p>
Sometimes we want to create an ordered list of a certain length from a larger pool of candidates.
<dl>
	<li>
		<title>permutation of size <m>k</m></title>
		<idx><h>permutation</h><h>of size <m>k</m></h></idx>
		<p> an ordered list of <m>k</m> elements from a given set <m>A</m>, with <m>\card{A} \ge k</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\permutation{n}{k}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\permutation{n}{k}</m></usage>
			<description>the number of permutations of size <m>k</m> taken from a set of size <m>n</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> the number of permutations of size <m>k</m> taken from a set of size <m>n</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title> <m>\permutationalt{n}{k}</m>, <m>\permutationaltalt{n}{k}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\permutationalt{n}{k}</m></usage>
			<description>alternative notation for <m>\permutation{n}{k}</m></description>
		</notation>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\permutationaltalt{n}{k}</m></usage>
			<description>alternative notation for <m>\permutation{n}{k}</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>alternative notation choices for <m>\permutation{n}{k}</m></p>
	</li>
</dl>
</p>

<example xml:id="example-permutations-size-2-from-4">
	<title>Visualizing <m>\permutation{4}{2}</m></title>
	<p>
	Consider <m>A = \{1,2,3,4\}</m>, so that <m>n = \card{A} = 4</m>.
	There are <m> 4! = 24 </m> permutations of <m>A</m>.
	</p>
	<figure>
		<caption>Permutations of a set of size <m>4</m>.</caption>
		<sidebyside>
			<tabular top="medium" halign="center">
				<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col /><col />
				<row bottom="minor">
					<cell><m>x</m></cell>
					<cell><m>1</m></cell>
					<cell><m>2</m></cell>
					<cell><m>3</m></cell>
					<cell><m>4</m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><m>\id_A(x)</m></cell>
					<cell><m>1</m></cell>
					<cell><m>2</m></cell>
					<cell><m>3</m></cell>
					<cell><m>4</m></cell>
				</row>
				<row bottom="minor">
					<cell><m>p_1(x)</m></cell>
					<cell><m>1</m></cell>
